    <id>2</id>
    <title>Combined summary - BIP 118 and SIGHASH_ANYPREVOUT</title>
    <updated>2026-07-11T05:37:06.872343+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2020-August/018079.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <published>2020-07-09 21:40:00+00:00</published>
    <summary>Anthony Towns has recently opened a draft pull request to update Bitcoin Improvement Proposal (BIP) 118 with the ANYPREVOUT bip. This decision, made after discussions with Christina, who is Christian Decker, aims to update the existing BIP rather than creating a new number. The updated BIP does not include chaperone signatures and makes changes to ANYPREVOUTANYSCRIPT, specifically not committing to the value. These updates are detailed in the text available on GitHub for community feedback, although it lacks tested code at this stage.
Further communication within the bitcoin-dev community highlighted a proposed construction by ZmnSCPxj known as the Decker-Russell-Osuntokun construction. This concept involves a single internal taproot pubkey, P = MuSig(A, B), for a channel between two parties. The structure allows update transactions signed using `SIGHASH_ANYPREVOUTANYSCRIPT` with monotonically increasing `nLockTime`, while state transaction inputs require an `nSequence` for relative locktime adherence. This setup suggests that each state transaction can only spend the specific update transaction it's linked to. However, broader concerns about relay-based attacks and their implications for HTLC security were raised, indicating the need for careful consideration of transaction relays without full knowledge of a node’s mempool/active chain.
Significant discussion also revolved around the potential use of SIGHASH_NOINPUT and SIGHASH_ANYPREVOUT in the context of relay attacks and their impact on Lightning Network operations. It was discussed how these mechanisms could simplify protocols if nodes could intelligently handle transaction replacements. This includes scenarios where nodes must identify and replace transactions based on conflicting spends within the mempool, which remains a complex challenge potentially requiring an advanced relay network among Lightning nodes.
In essence, these discussions reflect ongoing efforts to optimize Bitcoin’s underlying protocols, improve security measures against possible attacks, and enhance the efficiency of transactions, especially in the context of the Lightning Network. All contributors, including Anthony Towns, Christian Decker, and others, emphasize the need for community engagement and further testing to address the technical complexities and ensure robust implementation of these proposals.</summary>
